The paper deals with the analysis of deep neural networks, specifically investigating the role of depth and interpretation of intermediate layers. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper uses dynamical systems and differential equations to model the feature maps, which falls under the sub-category of Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE). The paper also mentions the use of Wasserstein geometry, which is a topic in Information Theory (cs.IT). The paper's focus on the transport map and its relation to the flow representation suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category of Systems and Control (cs.SY). Finally, the paper mentions the denoising autoencoder and its application to image processing, which falls under the sub-category of Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV).
